last_replies.name: Anonymous
last_replies.com:
(2/3)
Once you've learned a lot with Java or whatever, I highly recommend checking out C. Not C# or C++, just C. It is a very small language, and stripping you of the features and safeties that you got used to in Java forces you to think and program more strategically and efficiently. It's very nice, and for added learning benefits, I highly recommend not using an IDE for C and instead just using a command-line compiler and learning to read the error messages generated by your compiler, plus learning to use command-line tools like gdb and valgrind for debugging and memory checking, respectively. Also try to make decently large projects in C by learning to use makefiles. Digging into this lower-level way of development will help you later in your learning path after you've ditched the lower-level stuff and start using Visual Studio and things--it teaches you what's going on behind the scenes. Having a greater understanding of your build process is invaluable, in my opinion.

Also look into learning Data Structures, which are basically patterns of programming that allow for more efficient storing and retrieval of data. At this point any book and language will do, and you should be proficient enough to look at the patterns of whatever language and learning resource you're referencing and apply it to your own programs. This is really good for learning to optimize your code and make things faster, plus it's just really good practice in general.

last_replies.name: Anonymous
last_replies.com:
(3/3)
Finally, I highly highly highly recommend just taking what you've learned and trying to build something cool. Try to make a game. Or something. Whatever you think is cool. At this point you should be very skilled at using google and quickly finding out how to do things that you don't currently know how to do. Basically, self-learning is a skill and you should be proficient enough at this point to self-learn how to make your own video game, or web application, or whatever, just by using free resources that are available to you all over the internet.

What else can I say about this? Trying to build something you're passionate about because you think it's cool helps you a lot, because it not only motivates you even harder to keep learning, it also forces you to think inventively and creatively. For me, doing my own projects has taught me more than any course or book could have taught me on their own. Best of luck OP
